static boolean paren_balanced(String s) {
    //Your code here

    Stack<Character> pstack = new Stack<Character>();

    int len = s.length();
    char[] string_s = s.toCharArray();

    for(int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        if (string_s[i] == '(') pstack.push(string_s[i]);
        if (string_s[i] == ')') { 
          if (pstack.isEmpty()) return false;
          else {
            char top_elem = pstack.pop();
            if (top_elem == ')') return false;
          } 
        }
    }
    return pstack.isEmpty();

  }

}
```

The solution above works because:
* The code iterates through the input string. 
* When the code encounters an open parenthesis, the code pushes the parenthesis to the stack. 
* When the code encounters a closed parenthesis, the code checks to see whether a matching open parenthesis is on the top of the stack. If the stack is empty or there is no matching open parenthesis, the code returns False because the input string was not balanced.
* If the code has iterated through each character of the string and the stack is empty, this means that the parentheses were balanced and the code returns True.

